cs.NI, cs.CR, cs.SI, cs.DC, cs.IT 

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as it deals with Internet eXchange Points (IXPs) and their impact on the performance, evolution, security, and economics of the Internet. The paper also introduces a tool that augments the traceroute tool to identify IXPs in end-to-end paths. 

It could also belong to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as the paper mentions the impact of IXPs on the security of the Internet infrastructure. 

Additionally, it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as the paper deals with the flow of traffic in the Internet and how end-users can have more transparency over it. 

It could also belong to cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) as the paper deals with the infrastructure of the Internet and how it affects its performance. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.IT (Information Theory) as the paper deals with the transmission of information in the Internet and how it can be traced through IXPs.
